JOHANNESBURG Chairperson of the African Union (AU) Commission, Moussa Faki Mahamat, welcomed the United Nations Security Council s (UNSC) authorisation for the deployment of a Joint Force for the Group of Five for the Sahel States (FC-G5S).The five countries were Burkina Faso, Chad, Mali, Mauritania and Niger.Mahamat reiterated the importance of the FC-G5S in addressing the persistent threats of violent extremism and transnational organised crimes including arms, drugs and human trafficking with the aim of protecting civilians and promoting peace, security and stability in the region.READ: AU commission chair visits Sahel Saharan regionHe once again commended the resolve and sustained efforts by governments of Burkina Faso, Chad, Mali, Mauritania and Niger to guarantee the security of lives and properties of its citizens.The chairperson appealed to the member states to contribute troops and resources to the mission and encouraged adherence to the AU Strategy for the Sahel on the promotion of regional security co-operation through information exchange, border security and confidence-building measures between countries in the region to consolidate the gains made against the insurgency.Mahamat highlighted the importance of the international community s unequivocal support in the fight against terrorism and violent extremism and thanked the international community for its financial and technical support.Earlier this month, two people were killed by jihadists in a popular tourist resort in Mali.Chad saw an influx Nigerian refugees, who were fleeing the Boko Haram insurgency, while Niger battles the same extremists in its south-east.Last year January, dozens were killed in Burkina Faso's capital Ouagadougou by Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb. African News Agency